{{Short description|Japanese ornamental finial}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}
{{italic title}}
{{Hatnote|This article is about the Japanese architectural decoration. ''Gibōshi'' may also refer to the [[:en:Welsh onion|Welsh onion]] ''(Allium fistulosum)'' or to [[hosta]]s.}}
{{More citations needed|date=September 2014}}
{{Nihongo|'''''Gibōshi'''''|擬宝珠}} is a type of ornamental {{ill|Finial|en|Finial|qid=Q1406758|lt=Finial}} used on {{ill|Japan|en|Japan|qid=Q17|lt=Japan}}ese railings.<ref name=Gibo>{{cite web|title=Giboshi|url=http://www.aisf.or.jp/~jaanus/deta/g/giboshi.htm|publisher=Japanese Architecture and Art Net Users System (JAANUS)|access-date=9 January 2013}}</ref> ''Gibōshi'' bridge ornaments resemble an {{ill|onion|en|onion|qid=Q23485|lt=onion}}; the ends are bulbous and typically come to a point. It is believed that the shape of ''gibōshi'' was from ''hōju'' ({{lang|ja|宝珠}}; "sacred gem" or ''"{{ill|Cintamani|en|Cintamani|qid=Q2963837|lt=Cintamani}}"'') which is used to decorate roofs.<ref name=":0" /> They are often found on bridges in {{ill|Japanese garden|en|Japanese garden|qid=Q15835|lt=Japanese garden}}s, temples and {{ill|Shinto shrine|en|Shinto shrine|qid=Q845945|lt=Shinto shrine}}s.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.morikunijapan.com/product/giboshi/|title=Giboshi/Product information｜Japanese traditional architecture decoration. MORIKUNI Co., Ltd|website=www.morikunijapan.com|language=ja|access-date=2018-01-03}}</ref>

''Gibōshi'' come in two styles; normal style and {{ill|Kamakura period|en|Kamakura period|qid=Q236205|lt=Kamakura}} style.<ref name=":0" />
[[File:Giboshi Nijo Castle.JPG|thumb|A giboshi]]

